# RE-AUTHORED under lead-ktpz (→ shopsystem-templates) to fix a BC-caught Phase-1
# defect: prior 211 (@scenario_hash:d5d65b9cfedc24c1, now SUPERSEDED) paired a
# universal mandating the EXACT "${OVERRIDE:-default}" syntax for EVERY OPS_* key
# with the requirement that OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT carry the rule "<slug>-{bc}-beads".
# Those interact destructively: OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT="${OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT:-<slug>-{bc}-beads}"
# makes bash close the parameter expansion on the FIRST "}" (after "{bc"), so sourcing
# yields the CORRUPT "<slug>-{bc-beads}" and a consumer's later "{bc}" substitution
# silently no-ops. Per ADR-043 D1/D5/D6 {bc} integrity is REQUIRED in Phase-1, and
# per ADR-038 D3 the intent is OVERRIDABILITY, not a specific syntax — so the universal
# is RELAXED to require placeholder-safe overridability, and a new Then PINS that
# OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT resolves to "<slug>-{bc}-beads" with "{bc}" intact after sourcing.
#
# NET-NEW under lead-ow4d (ADR-043 Phase-1 keystone, gate on lead-kdsq templates
# release), pinning the RENDER half of the single ops-coordinates artifact ADR-043
# D2 FINALIZED (2026-06-28, lead-7wta): "shop-templates bootstrap" writes ONE
# rendered, directly shell-sourceable "KEY=value" env-file at "bin/ops-coordinates",
# derived from the manifest "product:" root, carrying the slug-NEUTRAL OPS_* keys
# each env-overridable in a placeholder-safe form (ADR-038 D3 precedence inline). This is the producer counterpart to the CONSUMER scenarios
# 204 (@scenario_hash:b7ea0de32ef49854) and 205 (@scenario_hash:1885dea2b4550fde),
# which require "bin/shop-shell" to SOURCE this artifact and carry only "$OPS_*"
# references — they remain VALID and COEXIST; this scenario pins that the sourced
# artifact actually EXISTS and resolves their load-bearing keys non-empty (notably
# OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE, ADR-046 — 205 sources it with NO literal fallback, so an
# unrendered key would resolve the launch image empty).
#
# OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE default is the canonical PRODUCT-NEUTRAL value (ADR-046:
# adopters still pull the same default image), hence constant across the Examples
# slugs while the slug-derived keys (OPS_SLUG/OPS_NETWORK/container names) vary.
# OPS_ORG is deliberately NOT pinned to a concrete value here: it is an
# origin-derived placeholder the footing runtime fills (ADR-043 D4/D6), so this
# scenario asserts only that the key is DEFINED by sourcing, not its render-time value.
#
# ARCHITECT FLAGS (do NOT act here — PO authoring only):
#   - Scenario 174 (@scenario_hash:f7af63457d95962f) enumerates the bootstrap ops
#     file-set as EXACTLY FIVE shop-owned files with an exclusivity premise;
#     "bin/ops-coordinates" is a NEW shop-owned ops file, so 174 must grow to
#     include it (cf. lead-y9e2, which already tracks 174 growth + the lead-a115
#     converged_ops exclusivity that must be re-superseded in lockstep). Flagged
#     for the architect; NOT edited here.
#   - @bc: and the reproducing @scenario_hash on dispatch are the Architect's;
#     the block-only @scenario_hash below is the PO's authoring hash.
@scenario_hash:0a3a8267109b5792
Scenario Outline: bootstrap of a "lead" shop named "<slug>" renders the single shell-sourceable ops-coordinates artifact at "bin/ops-coordinates" (the ADR-043 D2 derivation root) — a "KEY=value" env-file derived from the manifest "product:" root whose OPS_* keys are each environment-overridable (an external override taking precedence over the rendered default, in a placeholder-safe form for any key whose default carries a literal brace) — so that "source bin/ops-coordinates" defines the load-bearing coordinate variables that the rendered "bin/shop-shell" and the other "bin/" ops scripts consume, with the consumer keys (notably OPS_NETWORK, the container-name keys, and OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE) resolving to non-empty values and never an empty launch reference, and with OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT preserving its literal "{bc}" placeholder through sourcing
  Given an existing git repository at a target directory "/tmp/example-lead-shop" with no "bin/" subdirectory
  When I invoke the "shop-templates" bootstrap entry point with shop type "lead", shop name "<slug>", and target directory "/tmp/example-lead-shop"
  Then the exit code is 0
  And after the invocation the target directory contains a file at "bin/ops-coordinates" not under any ".claude/" subdirectory
  And sourcing "bin/ops-coordinates" in a bash shell succeeds with exit code 0 and defines the shell variables OPS_SLUG, OPS_NETWORK, OPS_POSTGRES_CONTAINER, OPS_VAULT_CONTAINER, OPS_VAULT_NAME, OPS_BROKER_ADDR, OPS_POSTGRES_PORT, OPS_VAULT_API_PORT, OPS_VAULT_PROXY_PORT, OPS_DATA_ROOT, OPS_LEAD_BEADS_REPO, OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT, OPS_ORG, and OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE
  And each OPS_* key in "bin/ops-coordinates" is rendered so that an override value exported before sourcing takes precedence over its rendered default; for a key whose rendered default contains no shell-significant braces this is the environment-overridable parameter expansion of the form OPS_X="${<OVERRIDE>:-<rendered-default>}", while a key whose rendered default carries a literal placeholder brace (notably OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT, whose value is the rule "<slug>-{bc}-beads") is instead rendered in a placeholder-safe form — outside the "${:-}" default, or with the braces escaped — that still honors an external override yet leaves the literal "{bc}" placeholder intact after sourcing
  And after sourcing with no override environment set, OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT resolves to "<slug>-{bc}-beads" with the literal "{bc}" placeholder intact (for the "shopsystem" example, "shopsystem-{bc}-beads"), so that a consumer performing a later "{bc}" substitution is not silently no-op'd by a placeholder destroyed during sourcing
  And after sourcing with no override environment set, OPS_SLUG resolves to "<slug>", OPS_NETWORK resolves to "<slug>", OPS_POSTGRES_CONTAINER resolves to "<slug>-postgres", and OPS_VAULT_CONTAINER resolves to "<slug>-agent-vault"
  And after sourcing with no override environment set, OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE resolves to the canonical product-neutral default "ghcr.io/dstengle/shopsystem-bc-lead:latest" regardless of "<slug>"
  And after sourcing, each of the load-bearing consumer keys OPS_NETWORK, OPS_POSTGRES_CONTAINER, OPS_VAULT_CONTAINER, and OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE resolves to a non-empty value, so the rendered "bin/shop-shell" never resolves an empty docker network, an empty container reference, or an empty launch image
  And exporting "<SLUG_UPPER>_POSTGRES_PORT" with value "<override_port>" before sourcing makes OPS_POSTGRES_PORT resolve to "<override_port>" rather than its rendered default, demonstrating the env-overridable precedence end-to-end

  Examples:
    | slug       | SLUG_UPPER | override_port |
    | shopsystem | SHOPSYSTEM | 6000          |
    | dummyco    | DUMMYCO    | 6001          |
